04966nam a22008055i 9783110714685DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107146857 a10.1515/97831107146852doi  a(DE-B1597)566533  a(OCoLC)1394872389  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a305.9069180967431 aButter, Inge, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNomadic Connectivity :bAn Ethnography of Walad Djifir Navigating Insecurities in Central Africa /cInge Butter. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XXV, 228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConnectivity and Society in Africa ,x2628-6564 ;v3  aPhDcLeiden Universityd2020.00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of maps, tables, figures, and photographs -- tOn transcription choices and translation -- tMaps -- tFamily trees -- tFerīkh individuals -- tChapter 1. Researching nomadic connectivity -- tChapter 2. Contextualizing itineraries -- tChapter 3. Brothers in arms -- tChapter 4. The walk of life -- tChapter 5. New mobilities and old mistrusts -- tChapter 6. Family and belonging in times of crisis -- tChapter 7. The everyday wilderness -- tBibliography -- tGlossary of Chadian Arabic and French terms -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA focus on the everyday has produced this ethnography, which hopes to give a nuanced voice to an extended family of semi-sedentary nomads, living at the centre of a country and region known for its political turmoil, ecological insecurities, and socio-economic hardship. The everyday of the Chadian Walad Djifir is one in which sedentarity and mobility are approached as two entwined parts of a whole, and where economic and geographical boundaries do not necessarily form constrictions. The ferīkh (nomadic camp) is where all of the Walad Djifir’s networks meet, and often also begin— a physical place embodying various networks and connections, which span time and geographical space. This analytical and methodological approach gives insight in how regional trends can be understood in light of the Walad Djifir’s daily lives. Over time, the Walad Djifir have developed ways of coping and dealing with insecurities, interacting with infrastructural, technological, and socio-political developments in specific ways. In exploring how such insecurities and crises become anchored into the everyday, the ferīkh provides answers. It is precisely the mundane elements of daily life which anchor disruption.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMobilität. 4aSedentarismus. 4aUnsicherheitsstudien. 4aZentralafrika.  aCentral Africa.  aInsecurity studies.  aMobility.  aSedentarism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831107148070 cprintz978311071460940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311071468540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110714685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110714685/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_SN  aE